To evaluate the usefulness of discourse motifs, we integrate them into three baseline models: random forests (RF), graph attention network (GAT), and Longformer \citep{beltagy2020longformer}. We illustrate RF is selected 
\dk{Provide a justification of why these models are chosen. Use the models used in prior work as reference. The baseline part is quite weak in my opinion, so provide a good jusitication here.}
Rather than using all of the size-3, 6, and 9 motifs, we selected motifs whose difference in MF-IDF scores is above the mean difference by at least one standard deviation. This resulted in 207 (31 + 96 + 80) selected motifs and we used their normalized counts as additional information (denoted as ``Sel. Motifs'' in Table \ref{tab:overall_f1}) when training GAT and Longformer. Specifically, we concatenate a small vector of 207 dimensions to the mean-pooled representation of GAT and to the \textsc{[CLS]} representation of Longformer, respectively. We describe more details of the experiment in Appendix \S\ref{sec:app:authorship_detection}.

\subsubsection{Edge-Based Explanations}\label{subsubsec:network_motifs_founded_on_edge_based_explanations}
When we have a labeled dataset and a trained graph neural networks (GNNs) for the authorship detection task, we can utilize explainability methods like ``GNNExplainer'' \citep{ying2019gnnexplainer} and ``GraphFramEx'' \citep{amara2022graphframex} that elucidate the predictions of GNNs by identifying the nodes or edges whose masking has the most significant impact on the predicted outcome. Since our graphs consist of directed and labeled edges, we require an explanation method tailored to edge-based features for graph attention network (GAT) \citep{velickovic2018graph}. Thus, we employ ``AttentionExplainer'' from GraphFramEx which computes edge masks using the attention coefficients generated by GATs trained on the binary classification task.

