\section{Experimental Setup}
Following the generation of three sets of potential discourse motifs for single-, double-, and triple-triads (\S\ref{subsec:discourse_motifs}), we evaluate them using the MF-IDF metric and retain those with scores surpassing at least one standard deviation. This yields a total of 207 motifs, with a detailed breakdown presented in Table \ref{tab:three_selected_motifs_sizes}.

\begin{table}[!h]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.5\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c|c}
        \toprule
        Size-3 & Size-6 & Size-9 \\
        \midrule
        31 & 96 & 80 \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Number of selected discourse motifs with MF-IDF scores exceeding the threshold of at least one standard deviation.}
    \label{tab:three_selected_motifs_sizes}
\end{table}

Section \ref{subsec:baseline} outlines the utilization of our proposed features (\S\ref{sec:revealing_key_patterns}) within both the baseline models and analyses; and Section \S\ref{subsec:datasets} describes the datasets designated and proposed for experimentation.


\subsection{Baseline Models}\label{subsec:baseline}
\begin{figure}[!ht]
\centering
% <left> <lower> <right> <upper>
{\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth,trim={0.01cm 0.0cm 0.04cm 0.01cm},clip]{figures/pipeline.pdf}}
\caption{A data flow diagram illustrating how various types of input features are fed into the three baseline models: Graph Attention Network (GAT), Random Forest (RF), and Longformer (LF).\vspace{-5mm}}
\label{fig:pipeline}
\end{figure}


To evaluate the usefulness of discourse motifs, we integrate them into three baseline models: Random Forest (RF) \citep{breiman2001random}, Graph Attention Network (GAT) \citep{velickovic2018graph}, and Longformer (LF) \citep{beltagy2020longformer}.
Figure \ref{fig:pipeline} depicts an overall mechanism of various types of input features being processed by the different models. From RF to LF, we introduce a greater number of model parameters and increase the granularity of inputs. RF is chosen to evaluate the baseline performance solely based on the structural information (i.e., discourse motif features) without considering the semantic content of the text. GAT receives the EDU-level representation of the texts as initial node embeddings, along with the discourse edge labels as edge embeddings. The discourse motif features are then appended to the mean-pooled representation of the graph. LF is initialized with pretrained weights\footnote{\textsc{allenai/longformer-base-4096} available on HuggingFace} and fed with the entire sequence of texts, in addition to the discourse motif features concatenated to the final layer of LF.





% feature integration 

RF: features only, Longformer, Ignore satelite info text and motifs. Specify variations by notations.

Rather than using all of the size-3, 6, and 9 motifs, we selected motifs whose difference in MF-IDF scores is above the mean difference by at least one standard deviation. This resulted in 207 (31 + 96 + 80) selected motifs and we used their normalized counts as additional information (denoted as ``Sel. Motifs'' in Table \ref{tab:overall_f1}) when training GAT and Longformer. Specifically, we concatenate a small vector of 207 dimensions to the mean-pooled representation of GAT and to the \textsc{[CLS]} representation of Longformer, respectively. We describe more details of the experiment in Appendix \S\ref{sec:app:authorship_detection}.


\subsubsection{Edge-Based Explanations}\label{subsubsec:network_motifs_founded_on_edge_based_explanations}
When we have a labeled dataset and a trained graph neural networks (GNNs) for the authorship detection task, we can utilize explainability methods like ``GNNExplainer'' \citep{ying2019gnnexplainer} and ``GraphFramEx'' \citep{amara2022graphframex} that elucidate the predictions of GNNs by identifying the nodes or edges whose masking has the most significant impact on the predicted outcome. Since our graphs consist of directed and labeled edges, we require an explanation method tailored to edge-based features for graph attention network (GAT) \citep{velickovic2018graph}. Thus, we employ ``AttentionExplainer'' from GraphFramEx which computes edge masks using the attention coefficients generated by GATs trained on the binary classification task. 
\dk{This section is not clear. From what written here, did you use the edge masks as one of features for your motifs? In my understanding, I thought you just used them for comparison, showing the correlation, instaed of features. If my understanding is correct, I'm not sure here is a good place to discuss about it. }

\subsection{Datasets}\label{subsec:datasets}
Our experiments are conducted on two existing benchmark datasets and one new dataset (\textsc{TenPageStories}) that we created for more in-depth analysis.

\paragraph{\textsc{HC3-English}.} \citet{guo2023close} published the first corpus on human writer vs. ChatGPT comparison. It comprises 24K \textit{paired} responses from human authors and ChatGPT for mostly question-answering (QA) style prompts across 5 domains: Reddit-ELI5, medicine, finance, open QA, and Wikipedia-CS.

