\begin{abstract}
The proliferation of powerful instruction-tuned large language models (LLMs) has led to a surge in machine-generated texts across various domains. Identifying the authorship of these texts has become a considerable challenge, with implications ranging from educational contexts to online advertising. While efforts have been made to distinguish machine-generated from human-authored texts, existing classifiers face challenges, particularly with out-of-domain samples and susceptibility to paraphrasing attacks.

This paper delves into the underlying nature of human-written texts, posing questions about discernible properties unique to texts crafted by humans and whether these properties extend beyond surface structure. Drawing inspiration from discourse analysis in linguistics, we introduce a novel approach involving hierarchical parse trees and recursive hypergraphs. By conducting network motif analysis, we uncover distinctive discourse patterns prevalent in texts generated by machines and humans.

Our empirical findings reveal that the utilization of "discourse motifs" shows promise in exploring linguistic signatures beyond the surface level. Both LLMs and humans generate distinct discourse patterns influenced by domains, with human-written texts exhibiting more "evenly branched out" discourse trees based on formality. Importantly, we demonstrate that integrating hierarchical discourse-level features enhances and robustifies authorship detection. Addressing a critical gap in existing research, we contribute a dataset specific to the creative writing domain, featuring longer-form machine-generated content up to 8K tokens.

Contributions:

Presentation of empirical findings supporting the use of "discourse motifs" in exploring linguistic signatures.
Demonstration that integrating hierarchical discourse-level features enhances authorship detection.
Construction of a comprehensive dataset for longer-form machine-generated content in the creative writing domain.



In the era of large language models (LLMs) where the distinction between human-written and machine-generated texts is getting blurry, this paper poses and investigates the question of the existence of discernible, unique linguistic properties within texts crafted by human writers. Positing that these linguistic signatures may lie beyond surface structure, we utilize discourse analysis in linguistics and introduce a novel approach involving hierarchical parse trees and recursive hypergraphs to uncover distinctive discourse patterns in texts generated by LLMs and humans. Empirical findings highlight that human writers tend 




the promise of "discourse motifs" in exploring linguistic signatures, revealing that both LLMs and humans generate distinct discourse patterns influenced by domains. Integration of hierarchical discourse-level features enhances authorship detection, and a unique dataset for longer-form machine-generated content in the creative writing domain is contributed, filling a critical gap in existing research. The study contributes valuable insights into the evolving landscape of machine-generated texts and the quest for robust authorship detection methods.









\end{abstract}

