Similarly, Figure \ref{fig:diff_dist_ten_page_stories} elucidates the distinct motif distributions within \textsc{TenPageStories} across various settings. We can see that the motifs indexed at 0 (Elaboration) and 5 (Joint) seem useful in detecting machine- and human-written texts, respectively. This may imply that human authors tend to construct narratives with a higher prevalence of Joint relations, indicative of more evenly branching structures, in contrast to the patterns found in texts generated by LLMs. Another noteworthy observation is the heightened occurrence of the motif indexed at 28 (Temporal) with increasing text length to generate.



\subsection{From Local Discourse Motifs to Global Structural Patterns}\label{subsec:local_to_global}
We found the observation (\S\ref{subsubsec:key_motifs}) that human-written texts for more \textit{formal} and \textit{discussional} domains, e.g., news summarization (\textsc{XSum}) and ChangeMyView (\textsc{cmv}), seem to contain more ``Joint'' discourse relations, wherein the corresponding child subgraphs are of equal importance (i.e., both are ``nuclei''). While this finding seems to corroborate our main assumption that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts; it is based on the statistics of local discourse motifs albeit computed over the whole graphs. In this section, we aim to extend our analysis to include global structures by (1) computing the correlation between the number of hyperedge relations (denoted as ``hyp.'' in Fig. \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}) present in graphs and the formality score of the corresponding document (\S\ref{subsubsec:formality_scorer}); and (2) investigating the overall shape variations of document graphs across different domains (\S\ref{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain}).

