\section{Results}\label{sec:experimental_results}

In this section, we present findings from four sets of experiments:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item Preliminary analyses of discourse motifs based on our proposed metrics (\S\ref{subsec:motif_analyses})
    \item Evaluation of the utility of discourse motifs in the authorship detection task including the ``paraphrase attack'' scenario (\S\ref{subsec:authorship_detection})
    \item Analyses of discourse motifs within the context of global structures (\S\ref{subsec:local_to_global})
    \item Exploration of patterns of discourse motifs for creative writing domain using our proposed dataset, \textsc{TenPageStories} (\S\ref{subsec:creative_writing})
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Preliminary Analyses on Discourse Motifs}\label{subsec:motif_analyses}
We begin our analyses by first investigating the correlation between the proposed discourse motifs and influential edges identified by the GAT explainer described in Section \ref{sec:exp_setup}

\subsubsection{Relationship between Motifs and Influential Edges for Explanation}
As a way to evaluate the appropriateness of using network motifs, we explore how they are related to influential edges in Graph Neural Network (GNN) computed by an explanation method.
Note that the influential edges mean edges with high masking values\footnote{The most influential edges whose masking values are larger than $0.99$ are considered in $[0, 1]$.} generated by a graph neural network explainer as described in (\S\ref{sec:exp_setup}).
We then calculate a correlation between frequencies of selected network motifs based on MF-IDF scores and those of influential edges.
To this end, we define two random variables as follows. Let $X$ be the number of single-triads and let $Y$ be the number of influential edges for each graph.
Samples of $X$ and $Y$ are collected from each graph in the datasets (\textsc{HC3-English}, \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect}), and the Pearson correlation coefficient $r_{XY}$ is calculated. 

\begin{figure}[!t]
\centering
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/corr_3_valid_deepfake.png}\vspace{-3mm}
}
\caption{Correlation between selected single-triads with high MF-IDF scores and influential edges computed by a GAT explainer on \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} dataset.\vspace{-3mm}}
\label{fig:corr_m3}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[!t]
\centering
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/influential_edge_proportions_valid_deepfake.png}\vspace{-3mm}}
\caption{Proportions of labels of influential edges. Note that ``Non-influential'' refers to edges whose mask values are under the threshold. Note also that the value ``0.0\%'' in this figure does not indicate the zero, but a very small positive number like ``1e-5\%.''\vspace{-3mm}}
\label{fig:proportion_edge_label_m3}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:corr_m3} shows that frequencies of selected single-triads and influential edges are highly correlated with $r_{XY} \approx 0.99$, indicating that the network motifs may be useful features in determining the authorship of texts. 
\dk{But, then why not simply using GNNs? If discourse motifs are all possible subset relations that can be detected through GNNs, why do we still need discourse motifs? You can mention the explainability aspect and/or lingusitic grounding, etc.}
Figure \ref{fig:proportion_edge_label_m3} shows the proportion of edge labels (i.e., discourse relations) of influential edges. Note that the label ``/'' denotes the dummy hyperedge relation (``hyp.'').



\subsubsection{Difference Distributions of Motifs across Domains}\label{subsubsec:key_motifs}

\begin{figure}[!ht]
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/motif_m3_mfidf_scores_difference_for_motif_m3.pdf}
  \caption{
Difference in single-triad motif distribution of machine-generated and human-written texts for five different domains in \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} dataset.
  \dk{Can't read the discourse relationship texts. Can you remove the domain name from the figures and move them as sub-captions (or make it legend at the bottom left) to save the horizontal space? Also, make y-axis using e format (e.g., e-3) to save addditional space. 
  For relation annotations, I encourage you to annotate them on Powerpoint and make font size larger. }
  }
  \label{fig:found_motifs}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:found_motifs} shows bar plots for the difference distribution of single-triad motifs across the five domains of texts. Due to space constraints, the plots showcase the top 20 motifs for both machine and human-written texts.
\dk{Any mention of statistical signifance? Without it, nobody will buy this.}
The mean and standard deviation of differences ($\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}})$) are is 0.00012 and 0.0015, respectively. Notably, machine-generated texts tend to feature more motifs with Background relations, while human-written texts exhibit an inclination towards Temporal discourse relations in domains such as review writing (\textsc{yelp}) and story generation (\textsc{wp}), and contain more Joint relations in domains that demand formality or deeper logical depths (i.e., argument writing (\textsc{cmv}) and news summarization (\textsc{xsum}). We note that Joint discourse relation signifies cases where the corresponding child trees are of equal importance (i.e., ``nuclei'') and thus branched evenly.\footnote{We study this branching effect in Section \ref{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain}.}

