\caption{Overall detection F1 scores of models on the three datasets.}
\label{tab:overall_f1}
\end{table*}

\subsubsection{\textsc{TenPageStories}}\label{subsubsec:creative_writing}
In a more open-ended exploration, we deploy the trained LF model augmented with discourse motifs to analyze our \textsc{TenPageStories} dataset.

\begin{table}[!ht]
\centering
\resizebox{\columnwidth}{!}{
\begin{tabular}{c|ccc|ccc}
\toprule
\multirow{2}{*}{Models} & \multicolumn{3}{c|}{FIG} & \multicolumn{3}{c}{Constrained FIG} \\
                         & 1 & 3 & 5 & 1 & 3 & 5 \\
\midrule
Longformer               & 0.30 & 0.40 & 0.45 & 0.59 & 0.50 & 0.55 \\
Longformer + Sel. Motifs & \textbf{0.43} & \textbf{0.65} & \textbf{0.71} & \textbf{0.71} & \textbf{0.69} & \textbf{0.70} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}}
\caption{Overall detection F1 scores on \textsc{TenPageStories} where ``FIG'' refers to the ``fill-in-the-gap'' setting. The numbers 1, 3, and 5 indicate the number of paragraphs to be generated (or ``filled in'').}
\label{tab:overall_f1_ten_page_stories}
\end{table}

First, we check how the different generation settings affect the detection performance (Table \ref{tab:overall_f1_ten_page_stories}). As expected the detection model performs better with longer generated texts (i.e., 1, 3, and 5 paragraphs). Also, when the first and last sentences of the human-written texts are additionally provided in the prompt (i.e., ``constrained FIG''), the corresponding generations are easier to detect. We note that the models' f1 scores are low as they produce a lot of false negatives, i.e., predicting actual human-written texts to be machine-generated. However, we can observe that the addition of a small discourse vector significantly improves the performance.


\begin{figure}[!ht]

\begin{subfigure}{\columnwidth}
% <left> <lower> <right> <upper>
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]
{figures/plot_motif_diff_FITG_paragraph_m3_motif_m3_hist_norm_by_edges.pdf}
\caption{\textit{Fill-in-the-gap} setting}
\end{subfigure}

\begin{subfigure}{\columnwidth}
\includegraphics[width=0.9\columnwidth]{figures/plot_motif_diff_FITG_FL_m3_motif_m3_hist_norm_by_edges.pdf}
\caption{\textit{Constrained fill-in-the-gap} setting}
\end{subfigure}
\caption{
Difference distribution of motifs for \textsc{TenPageStories} under the two \textit{fill-in-the-gap} settings. The x-axis represents unique indices of single-triads while the y-axis shows the difference in motif frequency (scaled by 1e-3) of machine-generated and human-written texts for each motif. Discourse motifs indexed at 0 (Elaboration), 5 (Joint), and 28 (Temporal) seem to be useful in distinguishing the two groups.}
\label{fig:diff_dist_ten_page_stories}
\end{figure}

Similarly, Figure \ref{fig:diff_dist_ten_page_stories} elucidates the distinct motif distributions within \textsc{TenPageStories} across various settings. We can see that the motifs indexed at 0 (Elaboration) and 5 (Joint) seem useful in detecting machine- and human-written texts, respectively. This may imply that human authors tend to construct narratives with a higher prevalence of Joint relations, indicative of more evenly branching structures, in contrast to the patterns found in texts generated by LLMs. Another noteworthy observation is the heightened occurrence of the motif indexed at 28 (Temporal) with increasing text length to generate.



\subsection{From Local Discourse Motifs to Global Structural Patterns}\label{subsec:local_to_global}
We found the observation (\S\ref{subsubsec:key_motifs}) that human-written texts for more \textit{formal} and \textit{discussional} domains, e.g., news summarization (\textsc{XSum}) and ChangeMyView (\textsc{cmv}), seem to contain more ``Joint'' discourse relations, wherein the corresponding child subgraphs are of equal importance (i.e., both are ``nuclei''). While this finding seems to corroborate our main assumption that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts; it is based on the statistics of local discourse motifs albeit computed over the whole graphs. In this section, we aim to extend our analysis to include more \textit{global structures} by (i) computing the correlation between the number of hyperedge relations (denoted as ``hyp.'' in Fig. \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}) present in graphs and the formality score of the corresponding document (\S\ref{subsubsec:formality_scorer}); 
% (ii) investigating the overall shape variations of document graphs across different domains (\S\ref{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain});
and (ii) comparing the variability in discourse structures of upper and lower parts of discourse graphs for original and paraphrased documents (\S\ref{subsubsec:upper_vs_lower}).

\subsubsection{Formality Scores and Hyperedges}\label{subsubsec:formality_scorer}

Concerning text styles, we note that the most noticeable disparity among the various text domains appears to lie in the formality dimension. Thus, we computed the formality score for every text generated by humans and machines (c.f. \S\ref{subsec:baseline}). Also, for every corresponding document graph, we count the (normalized) frequency of hyperedges for all motifs present in the graph. This is because the hyperedge relations represent higher-level abstractions of text and are thus linked to the discourse hierarchy. 
From there, we compute the Pearson correlation coefficient between the scores and frequencies.

\begin{table}[!ht]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.75\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c}
        \toprule
        Machine-Generated & Human-Written\\
        \midrule
        $0.08^*$ & $0.39^*$ \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Pearson's $R$ between formality scores and frequency of hyperedges.}
    \label{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}
\end{table}

As shown in Table \ref{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}, the human-written texts over all domains exhibit weak to moderate correlation with the formality style while machine-generated ones seem to show no correlation. This hints that when humans write more structured texts in terms of discourse, the contents are often more formal.

